dal-aAhu biguruwrK 
† He caused him to fall into that which he desired [to bring about] by exposing him to perdition, or destruction, or loss, without his knowledge; 
from UidolaMCu↓ Ald-alowi. (Ṣ.) 
[In the Ḳur vii. 21,] fadal-aAhumaA biguruwrK means † And he caused them to fall (fdl-AhmA) into disobedience by deceiving, or beguiling, them: so says Aboo-Is-ḥáḳ [Zj]: 
or † he excited their cupidity [with deceit, or guile]; originating from the case of a thirsty man's being let down (yudal-aI) into a well in order that he may satisfy his thirst from its water, and his not finding water in it, so that he is let down into it with deceit, or guile: or it means he emboldened them to eat of the tree with deceit, or guile; originally dal-alahumaA. (T.)

mudomajN, applied to a man, † Well knit together, like a rope firmly twisted; 
as also manodamijN↓: and in like manner, mudomajaAtu Alxaloqi, applied to women, † of a frame well knit together; 
and so dum-ajN↓, of which ISd found no singular. (L.) 
And accord. to Lth, 
mudam-ajN↓, applied to the back, and to a limb, or member, means † [Well compacted, or rounded, and smooth;] as though made round and smooth (Oudorijato wamul-isato) as when the female comber and dresser of hair plaits the locks of a woman's hair: (TA:) [or this may be a mistranscription for mudomajN; for it is said that] mudomajN signifies round and smooth; syn. mudamolajN; (Ḳ;) or mudorajN maEa malaAsatihi: (Ṣ:) and, applied to a back, made smooth. (L.)

